        "####\n",
        "---\n",
        "# Stage 9 *(TIme-Series Statistical Analysis)*\n",
        "---\n",
        "####"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "w1THxeRHbD-v"
      },
      "source": [
        "In the Walmart Dataset, there are 45 stores (nummbered 1-45) and each store has many departments (usually numbered 1 to 99, though not every store has every department)\n",
        "Sales are recorded weekly for each Store + Department combination\n",
        "\n",
        "This creates ~3,000–4,500 individual time series in total (one series per unique Store–Dept pair).\n",
        "When using classical time series models like ARIMA / SARIMA / SARIMAX:\n",
        "These models are traditionally designed to work on one single time series at a time (not thousands simultaneously).\n",
        "So for the purpose of this project, the weekly sales forecasting will be done on Store 1 and Dept 1."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "g3kAgP6Q_VGy"
      },
      "source": [
        "## **Data PreProcessing**"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "### **Checking which Store and Dept combination is more likely to have good time series.**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "1UmlI0wUGUbE"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# 1. Basic summary per Store-Depts\n",
        "summary = train_df.groupby(['Store', 'Dept']).agg(\n",
        "    weeks=('Date', 'count'),\n",
        "    mean_sales=('Weekly_Sales', 'mean'),\n",
        "    std_sales=('Weekly_Sales', 'std'),\n",
        "    max_sales=('Weekly_Sales', 'max'),\n",
        "    zero_weeks=('Weekly_Sales', lambda x: (x == 0).sum()),\n",
        "    holiday_weeks=('IsHoliday', 'sum')\n",
        ").reset_index()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Filter to reasonably complete series\n",
        "summary = summary[summary['weeks'] >= 120]  # at least ~120 weeks of data\n",
        "\n",
        "# Add coefficient of variation (lower = more stable pattern)\n",
